=============================================================================
@NODE DESCRIPTION

                                DESCRIPTION


PPack is a fast PowerPacker data @{"cruncher" LINK "DATA COMPRESSION"} and @{"decruncher"  LINK "DATA COMPRESSION"}.
The size of the speedup buffer is chosen depending on the available memory.

@ENDNODE

=============================================================================
@NODE REQUIREMENTS

                            SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS


@{"Kickstart" LINK COPYRIGHTS} 2.04
@{"Workbench" LINK COPYRIGHTS} 2.0
@{"powerpacker.library" LINK COPYRIGHTS} V35

@{"Workbench" LINK COPYRIGHTS} 2.1 for localized error messages

@ENDNODE

=============================================================================
@NODE "DATA COMPRESSION" "Some words about data compression"

                             DATA COMPRESSION


Data  compression is a technique to save disk storage space. With a program
like  PPack  you  can  compress  and decompress files. Compressed files are
shorter  than  decompressed  ones,  but  you have to decompress them before
reusing.

The jargon of compression program developers contains a lot of synonyms.

Synonyms for compress are: crunch or pack
Synonyms for decompress are: decrunch or depack

Therefore  PPack  and  other  programs  doing  compression  are  refered as
compressors, crunchers or packers.

Files  which  are  not  compressed  are  called  uncrunched or unpacked. To
decompress a file and compress it again is called recrunching or repacking.

By fault some persons use recrunch or repack where they should use decrunch
or depack instead.

@ENDNODE

=============================================================================
@NODE CONTENTS

                                 CONTENTS


This software package consists of the following files:

PPack_68000
		- PPack for all Amigas.

PPack_68020
		- PPack for Amigas equipped with an MC68020 CPU or better.
	   	  (slightly shorter and faster than PPack_68000)

PPack.guide
		- This AmigaGuide document for Multiview.

@{"Rexx/PPDecrunch.ced" LINK AREXX}
		- An ARexx script to decrunch files loaded into CygnusEd.

@{"Libs/powerpacker.library" LINK COPYRIGHTS}
		- The library needed by PPack.

@ENDNODE

=============================================================================
@NODE INSTALLATION

                               INSTALLATION

Simply  copy  the  appropriate version of PPack to a directory in your path
and rename it to PPack.

Type
	copy PPack_68000 to C:PPack
or
	copy PPack_68020 to C:PPack

if your Amiga has got an MC68020 CPU or higher.

Now you have to copy the powerpacker.library to your LIBS: directory.

	copy Libs/powerpacker.library to libs:

@ENDNODE

=============================================================================
@NODE USAGE

                                   USAGE


PPack <srcfile> {<srcfile>} [TO <destdir>] [EFFICIENCY 1-5] [NOSUFFIX]
                            [NOPER] [NODEL] [RECRUNCH] [ADDFILENOTE]
                            [CRYPT] [PASSWORD <password>]
Template:

  @{" FILES/A/M        " LINK FILES}  Source files
  @{" TO/K             " LINK TO}  Destination directory
  @{" EFF=EFFICIENCY/N " LINK EFFICIENCY}  1 - Fast, 2 - Med, 3 - Good, 4 - Very Good, 5 - Best.
  @{" NOPP=NOSUFFIX/S  " LINK NOSUFFIX}  No '.pp' suffix.
  @{" NOPER/S          " LINK NOPER}  No percentage progress indicator.
  @{" NODEL/S          " LINK NODEL}  Don't delete <srcfile>.
  @{" RECRUNCH/S       " LINK RECRUNCH}  Recrunch <srcfile>.
  @{" ADDFILENOTE/S    " LINK ADDFILENOTE}  Add PPack version filenote to destination file.
  @{" CRYPT/S          " LINK CRYPT}  Use requester to get password for (de)crypting.
  @{" PASSWORD/K       " LINK PASSWORD}  Crypt/Decrypt with <password>.


PPack  loads  <srcfile>,  then filename and size are shown and it's getting
packed   with  'BEST'  if  no  other  @{"efficiency"  LINK  EFFICIENCY}  is specified.
The  largest available speedup buffer is used. This means that PPack adapts
itself dynamically to the available free memory.

If <srcfile> is not found, PPack checks for <srcfile>.pp.

While  packing  the percentage of the already processed bytes and the ratio
between  the  packed file and the source file in percent is shown. Here you
can  hit ^C (CTRL+C) to stop the program, in this case no file is saved and
the program exits with returncode 10.

After  crunching the crunched size and the compression ratio are shown. The
file is saved as <srcfile>.pp and the original <srcfile> is deleted.

PPack automatically decrunches files already packed with PPack.

For  online help run PPack without any arguments to get a short description
of  the  options.  Or  use  PPack ? to get the command template in AmigaDOS
style.

Hit ^E or ^F to stop crunching of the current file only.

If an error happened PPack will fail with returncode 20.

PPack  is  not  localized,  but  DOS errors are printed in the language you
selected with the locale preference editor.

@ENDNODE


@NODE FILES

                                 FILES/M/A

The  FILES  argument  is the only one which is needed in all cases. You may
provide  one  or  more source files which will be processed. Unpacked files
will be crunched. Already packed files will be decrunched instead.

Crunch all files in a directory with:
	PPack ~(#?..pp)	;all files not ending in '.pp'

Decrunch all files in a directory with:
	PPack (#?..pp)	;all files ending in '.pp'
@ENDNODE

@NODE TO

                                   TO/K


PPack  places  the  destination files in the same directory than the source
files. Using the TO keyword you are able to specify a different destination
directory for the processed files.

Example: PPack readme.txt contents.txt TO RAM:

Will  pack  'readme.txt'  and  'contents.txt'  to  'RAM:readme.txt.pp'  and
'RAM:contents.txt.pp'.

@ENDNODE

@NODE EFFICIENCY

                             EFF=EFFICIENCY/K


You may pack files with different efficiencies.

Efficiencies are:
                  1 - fast 
                  2 - mediocre
                  3 - good
                  4 - very good
                  5 - best

A higher efficiency crunches better (shorter destination file) but it takes
more time to crunch and decrunch.

The  default efficiency of PPack is 5, because nowadays machines are faster
and  most  people have got an MC68020 CPU in their Amiga. This is different
from  the original PowerPacker programs which use 3 as a default. To use an
other  efficiency  than  the default one you have to provide the EFFICIENCY
keyword. You may use EFF as an abbreviation of EFFCIENCY, too.

Example: PPack sunset.iff EFFICIENCY=1
         Compresses 'sunset.iff' fast. 
@ENDNODE


@NODE NOSUFFIX

                              NOPP=NOSUFFIX/S


For  your convinience PPack saves the crunched files under a different name
than  the  original  files. For the destination file the name of the source
file  is  used  with  '.pp'  added  at  the  end.  This way you can easiliy
distinguish  between  packed  and unpacked files. If an icon exists for the
crunched  file  it  will  be renamed, too. To prevent PPack from adding the
suffix you may provide NOPP or NOSUFFIX as a switch.

Example: PPack nicepicture

Packs  'nicepicture'  to  'nicepicture.pp'.  If an error happens during the
writing  of  the  destination  file, it will be removed and the source file
will  not  be  deleted.  If 'nicepicture.info' exists it will be renamed to
'nicepicture.info.pp'.

Example: PPack nicepicture NOSUFFIX

Packs 'nicepicture' to 'nicepicture', overwriting the original. If an error
happens  during the write data may be lost. If 'nicepicture.info' exists it
will not be renamed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE NODEL

                                  NODEL/S


PPack  saves its destination files under a different name than the original
files if @{"NOSUFFIX" LINK NOSUFFIX} is not specified.

To prevent PPack from deleting the original file after the destination file
has  been saved successfully you may provide NODEL as a switch. This may be
handy together with the @{"TO" LINK TO} keyword to have some files crunched
in one directory and uncrunched in another one.

@ENDNODE

@NODE NOPER

                                  NOPER/S


If  NOPER  is  specified,  PPack will show no percentage progress indicator
thus  making  the crunching a bit faster. May be useful if PPack is used in
the background.

@ENDNODE

@NODE RECRUNCH

                                RECRUNCH/S


PPack  detects  already  packed  files  automatically.  This way PPack will
decrunch packed files without further options.

If  you  want to recrunch a packed file at an other @{"EFFICIENCY" LINK EFFICIENCY} use RECRUNCH
as a switch to crunch the data before writing the destination file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CRYPT

                                  CRYPT/S


PPack  is  able  to  encrypt  the  crunched  data  before  writing  to  the
destination  file.  This  way you may protect your files from other persons
eyes.

Use CRYPT as a switch to bring up a requester for entering the password.

Note: You will need the reqtools.library to use the crypt function as PPack
needs the library to open the requester window.

You  may  also  specify  the password directly in the commandline using the
@{"PASSWORD" LINK PASSWORD} keyword.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PASSWORD

                                PASSWORD/K


PPack  is  able  to  encrypt  the  crunched  data  before  writing  to  the
destination  file.  This  way you may protect your files from other persons
eyes.  You  may  specify the password directly in the commandline using the
PASSWORD keyword.

Example: 
	PPack secret.doc PASSWORD master&johnson

Generates a crunched and encrypted file called 'secret.doc.pp'.

	PPack  secret.doc.pp PASSWORD master&johnson

Decrypt and decrunch 'secret.doc.pp' to 'secret.doc'.


You  may  decrypt  and decrunch the file with the same PPack invocation you
used  to  encrypt it. If you do not specify the password in the commandline
PPack  will  prompt for it with a requester. For this feature you will need
the reqtools.library.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ADDFILENOTE

                               ADDFILENOTE/S


PPack  uses  the  source files filenote for the destination file, too. This
way no important information will get lost. But you may specify ADDFILENOTE
as  a switch to force PPack to add a comment like 'Crunched with PPack 1.1'
or  'Decrunched with PPack 1.1' to the destination file. The string depends
on  the  action  PPack  has  performed  (crunching  or decrunching) and the
version number.

@ENDNODE
=============================================================================
@NODE AREXX

                                   AREXX


The  ARexx  script is used to decrunch powerpacked files after loading them
into  CygnusEd.  You  will see 'PP20' in the first line of the text if it's
powerpacked.  Use  'Send  Dos/ARexx  command...'  to run the script. If the
script  doesn't  find the 'PP20' in the first line a requester will come up
telling  you  that  this isn't a Powerpacker data file. The script uses two
temporary  files  in  T:. This path has to be changed if you assigned T: to
RAM:T  (as  an  umodified  startup-sequence  does)  but  haven't got enough
memory.

For permanent use of the script, use any key you want as a macro invocation
to  call  'Send Dos/ARexx command...' or install it with 'Install Dos/ARexx
command...' to a Functionkey.

You  may  easily  change  this script for use on an other editor. If you've
done  this,  don't  hesitate  to  send  it  to  the  @{"author" LINK "Boris Folgmann"}, so it can
be included in the next release.

You should consider to optimize the script using RexxOpt.

@ENDNODE

